Of course. Security is a critical aspect of running code from any external source, including an AI model. I will enhance the Python sandboxing environment to be more robust by implementing stricter isolation measures.

I've updated the sandboxing service to explicitly disable network access, prevent the loading of new packages, and block access to browser APIs from within the Python environment. I've also introduced a 5-second execution timeout to prevent infinite loops or resource-intensive scripts from freezing the browser tab. These changes significantly harden the sandbox, ensuring that the agent's scripts run in a tightly controlled and secure context.

Here are the changes I've made to the application:

services/pyodide.ts

The sandboxing logic has been centralized and significantly enhanced. I have created a new Python prelude that runs before every script. This prelude explicitly removes access to potentially harmful modules like micropip (for package installation), socket and urllib (for networking), and js (for browser API access). The runPython function now wraps the execution in a Promise.race to enforce a timeout, and the mock DWSIM environment has been moved here to keep all sandbox-related code in one place.

services/geminiService.ts

I've updated the system prompt to inform the agent about the new sandbox restrictions. This is a crucial step for managing the agent's expectations, ensuring it doesn't attempt to perform actions like making network requests or installing packages, which would fail in the secured environment.

App.tsx

I have removed the DWSIM mock code from this file, as it is now part of the centralized sandboxing service. The handleRunScript function has also been simplified to reflect this change, making the component cleaner and more focused on its UI responsibilities.

These updates provide a much more secure foundation for executing the agent's Python scripts.
